TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dissecting Mechanisms of Financial Crises: Intermediation and Sentiment
AU  - Krishnamurthy, Arvind
AU  - Li, Wenhao
Y1  - 2024/10/03
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2025/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/733423
DO  - 10.1086/733423
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 935
EP  - 985
VL  - 133
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We develop a model of financial crises with both a financial amplification mechanism, via frictional intermediation, and a role for sentiment, via time-varying beliefs about an illiquidity state. The model accounts for the entire crisis cycle, matching data on the frothy precrisis behavior of asset markets and credit; the sharp transition to a crisis where asset values fall, disintermediation occurs, and output falls; and the slow postcrisis recovery in output. Both the intermediation and the belief mechanism are essential to match the crisis cycle. However, modeling the belief variation via either a Bayesian or a diagnostic model can match the broad patterns.
AB  - We develop a model of financial crises with both a financial amplification mechanism, via frictional intermediation, and a role for sentiment, via time-varying beliefs about an illiquidity state. The model accounts for the entire crisis cycle, matching data on the frothy precrisis behavior of asset markets and credit; the sharp transition to a crisis where asset values fall, disintermediation occurs, and output falls; and the slow postcrisis recovery in output. Both the intermediation and the belief mechanism are essential to match the crisis cycle. However, modeling the belief variation via either a Bayesian or a diagnostic model can match the broad patterns.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/733423
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/733423
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Scooped! Estimating Rewards for Priority in Science
AU  - Hill, Ryan
AU  - Stein, Carolyn
Y1  - 2024/10/03
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2025/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/733398
DO  - 10.1086/733398
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 793
EP  - 845
VL  - 133
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The scientific community assigns credit or ?priority? to individuals who publish an important discovery first. We examine the impact of losing a priority race (colloquially known as getting ?scooped?) on publication and career outcomes. To do so, we analyze data from structural biology where the nature of the scientific process together with the Protein Data Bank enables us to identify priority races and their outcomes. We find that scooped teams are less likely to publish in top journals and receive 21 percent fewer citations. We further study the implications of priority racing on research strategy, academic inequality, and scientist beliefs.
AB  - The scientific community assigns credit or ?priority? to individuals who publish an important discovery first. We examine the impact of losing a priority race (colloquially known as getting ?scooped?) on publication and career outcomes. To do so, we analyze data from structural biology where the nature of the scientific process together with the Protein Data Bank enables us to identify priority races and their outcomes. We find that scooped teams are less likely to publish in top journals and receive 21 percent fewer citations. We further study the implications of priority racing on research strategy, academic inequality, and scientist beliefs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/733398
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/733398
Y2  - 2026/04/24
